Patch Set 2: Code-Review-2

This has been discussed multiple times across past years and the end result has always been, no we're not removing them.

Patch Set 2:

The in-tree configs are updated just prior cutting the stable so we have accurate config examples available for the stable releases as well.

Patch Set 2:

Erno, fair enough - but that does put glance into a position where it is alone in doing this. Is the actual reason for keeping the file in-tree known, or is it just a 'tradition'?

Brian - you're right, devstack does need adjustment. I'm a little low on bandwidth right now to do it, but it would be best to get devstack updated asap to use generated conf files instead of the in-tree conf files... even if the project does insist on keeping it in-tree.

A suggestion - if the project decision is to keep it in-tree, then there should be a test which verifies that the in-tree version matches the generated version. If it does not, a patch should not pass tests. This is the only way to ensure that it's kept up to date as patches are submitted, and the in-tree file is therefore not misleading.

Patch Set 2:

The devstack change is https://review.openstack.org/527263

Patch Set 2:

I want to reopen the discussion, because these are always out of date in master (for example, did anyone remember to regenerate the config files before releasing Q-2?  I didn't think so.)  Generating the files is not an onerous burden on operators since they already have workflows for doing so with nova, cinder, and neutron.  And if updated info is being published to our documentation, I don't see what the problem is.
